== Appendix P: Norwegian Pronunciation == The pronunciation is indicated in [[w:IPA|IPA]]. The sounds are best learned from a native speaker. Whenever possible, practice these with a native speaker. Reading aloud will also help your confidence. Note that the Norwegian language is full of dialects, so there are several ways of pronouncing the words. Foreign learners are usually taught to speak the way that people in the Oslo-area speak. === Vowels === The Norwegian vowels:
{| width="50%" style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top |- align="center" | a | e | i | o | u | y | | | |}
The main rule is that long vowels occur before single consonants, short vowels occur before double consonants. This is no absolute rule, though, as you will see in the examples below. '''Notice''': the short '''o''' sound is actually never to be found written with an ''o''! (It's usually represented by ''u'')
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Vowel ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | a (short) | {{IPA|}} | h'''a'''tt | {{IPA|ht}} |- | a (long) | {{IPA|}} | h'''a'''t | {{IPA|ht}} |- | e (short) | {{IPA|e}} | s'''e'''nd | {{IPA|sen}} |- | e (long) | {{IPA|e}} | s'''e'''n | {{IPA|sen}} |- | i (short) | {{IPA|i}} | v'''i'''nd | {{IPA|vin}} |- | i (long) | {{IPA|i}} | v'''i'''n | {{IPA|vin}} |- | o (short) | {{IPA|u}} | b'''u'''kk | {{IPA|buk}} |- | o (long) | {{IPA|u}} | b'''o'''k | {{IPA|buk}} |- | u (short) | {{IPA|}} | l'''u'''nd | {{IPA|ln}} |- | u (long) | {{IPA|}} | l'''u'''n | {{IPA|ln}} |- | y (short) | {{IPA|y}} | l'''y'''nne | {{IPA|lyne}} |- | y (long) | {{IPA|y}} | l'''y'''n | {{IPA|lyn}} |- | (short) | {{IPA|}} | v''''''rt | {{IPA|vrt}} |- | (long) | {{IPA|}} | v''''''r | {{IPA|vr}} |- | (short) | {{IPA|}} | s''''''tt | {{IPA|st}} |- | (long) | {{IPA|}} | s''''''t | {{IPA|st}} |- | (short) | {{IPA|}} | v''''''tt | {{IPA|vt}} |- | (long) | {{IPA|}} | v''''''t | {{IPA|vt}} |}
=== Consonants === The Norwegian consonants : {| width="50%" style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top |- align="center" | b | d | f | g | h | j | k | l | m | n | p | r | s | t | v |}
Most consonants in the Norwegian language are pronounced like the English consonants.
==== Plosives ==== In Norwegian, there are six plosives, all equal to the English version of them.
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Consonant ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | p | p | ho'''pp''' | {{IPA|hp}} |- | b | b | la'''bb''' | {{IPA|lb}} |- | t | t | '''t'''ak | {{IPA|tk}} |- | d | d | la'''dd''' | {{IPA|ld}} |- | k | k | ta'''kk''' | {{IPA|tk}} |- | g | g | kna'''gg''' | {{IPA|kng}} |}
==== Fricatives ==== These are also quite equal to the English language, except that Norwegian does not have '''{{IPA|}}''', (as in ''thin'') '''{{IPA|}}''' (as in ''this'') '''{{IPA|}}''' (as in ''measure'') and '''{{IPA|z}}''', (as in ''zing'') but at the other hand, norwegians have the '''{{IPA|}}''' sound, which is sort of a ''stiffer'' version of the '''{{IPA|}}''' sound (as in German ''ich''). The '''''' sound is similar to the "h" in many English dialects' pronunciation of ''huge''.
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Consonant ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | f | f | '''f'''in | {{IPA|fin}} |- | v | v | '''v'''in | {{IPA|vin}} |- | s | s | la'''ss''' | {{IPA|ls}} |- | s(ky).../s(kj)... | {{IPA|}} | '''s'''kyt | {{IPA|yt}} |- | k(i).../k(j)... | {{IPA|}} | '''ki'''no | {{IPA|ino}} |- | j/g(j).../h(j).../g(i)<!-- no dots here, no continuation--> | j | '''g'''i | {{IPA|ji}} |- | h | h | '''h'''a | {{IPA|h}} |}
==== Nasals ====
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Consonant ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | m | m | la'''m''' | {{IPA|lm}} |- | n | n | va'''nn''' | {{IPA|vn}} |- | ng | {{IPA|}} | sa'''ng''' | {{IPA|s}} |}
==== Liquids ====
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Consonant ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | l | l | fa'''ll''' | {{IPA|fl}} |}
==== Trills ====
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 0.5em;" valign=top cellpadding=5 ! Consonant ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | r | r | p'''r'''v | prv |}
=== Diphthongs === Vowels also appear in set combinations. These are called diphthongs. They are two vowel sounds pronounced after the other as a continous sound
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 1em;" valign=top ! Diphthong ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | ei | i | v'''ei''' | vi |- | y | y | h'''y''' | hy |- | au | {{IPA|}} | s'''au''' | {{IPA|s}} |- | ai | {{IPA|i}} | k'''ai''' | {{IPA|ki}} |- | oy | {{IPA|y}} | konv'''oy''' | {{IPA|kunvy}} |- | ui | {{IPA|i}} | h'''ui''' | {{IPA|hi}} |- | oi | ui | h'''oi''' | hui |}
=== Allophonic Variants ===
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 1em;" valign=top ! IPA ! Example ! IPA |- | {{IPA|}} | ha'''rdt''' | {{IPA|h}} |- | {{IPA|}} | ve'''rd'''i | {{IPA|vi}} |- | {{IPA|}} | '''rl'''ig | {{IPA|i}} |- | {{IPA|}} | ga'''rn''' | {{IPA|g}} |}
=== Tonemes === Norwegian has two contrasting tonemes. These are kind of hard to describe using text, and some also say that foreigners (to Norway) are even unable to distinguish one from the other. However, they do exist. In the words indicated with 1 and a hacek, the tone is normal in the first part of the word, and rises in the last part of the word. In the words indicated with 2, the word is pronounced like any other normal word. (In other words, it's very hard to say 1 words in a monotone voice) Here are two examples:
{| style="background-color: #f2fff2; border: solid 1px #bfffbf; padding: 1em;" valign=top ! Example ! IPA !English word |- | b'''nd'''er | {{IPA|bnr}} |farmers |- | b'''nn'''er | {{IPA|bnr}} |beans |- | &nbsp; | &nbsp; |- | l'''o'''ven | {{IPA|lven}} |the law |- | l''''''ven | {{IPA|lven}} |the barn |}
'''Notice''': The two last examples are ''very'' similar to each other even though they are different, and I am actually somewhat unsure if it's loven or lven which is the more "special" one. <!--Someone correct me if they knnow.-->
